{
  "texts": [
    "Given a foundation F = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I ⟩, let F ♯ = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, RO(S, ⊑)⟩.",
    "Given a possibility frame F = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩, if RO(S, ⊑) is closed un- der ■ i for each i ∈ I, then we call (F ♯) ♯ = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, RO(S, ⊑)⟩ the associated full frame of F. ◁Many possibility frames may be based on the same foundation.",
    "Yet at most one full possibility frame may be based on a given foundationF.",
    "If F = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I ⟩ is such that RO(S, ⊑) is closed under ■ i, then F ♯ is the unique full possibility frame based on F. If RO(S, ⊑) is not closed under ■ i, then F ♯ isnot even a partial-state frame as in Definition 2.1.",
    "In § 2.3, we will give first-order conditions on the interplay of ⊑ and R i that are equivalent to RO(S, ⊑) being closed under ■ i; and in § 2.3 and § 5.5, we will see that every possibility frame can be turned into a modally equivalent one satisfying even stronger interplay conditions.The fact that closure of RO(F) under ∩ and ⊃ is guaranteed whereas closure under ■ i is an extra requirement is reflected in a syntactic fact: to embed classical modal logic into intuitionistic modal logic by an extension of the Gödel-Gentzen negative translation, the translation can simply \"pass through\" conjunctions and implications (and negations), but we must doublenegate the box formulas, as follows.Definition 2.26 (Modal Negative Translation)."
  ]
}